--- title: "Midterm and Final Project" author: "Justice Kessie" date: "2025-03-24" categories: [news, code, analysis] image: "image.jpeg" format: html: code-fold: true # Enables collapsible code blocks code-tools: true # Adds copy, toggle, and download buttons code-summary: "Show the code" # Optional: label for collapsed code --- ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # Install required packages if not already installed if (!require("leaflet")) install.packages("leaflet") if (!require("dplyr")) install.packages("dplyr") if (!require("RColorBrewer")) install.packages("RColorBrewer") if (!require("htmlwidgets")) install.packages("htmlwidgets") # Load libraries library(leaflet) library(dplyr) library(RColorBrewer) library(htmlwidgets) # Read the data lassa_data <- read.csv("lassa_virus_simulation_data.csv") # Prepare data for map map_data <- lassa_data %>% group_by(country, city, lat, long) %>% summarize( total_cases = n(), human_cases = sum(host == "human"), rodent_cases = sum(host == "rodent"), avg_fitness = mean(fitness), .groups = 'drop' ) # Create a color palette for the number of cases pal <- colorBin( palette = "YlOrRd", domain = map_data$total_cases, bins = 7 ) # Create the map lassa_map <- leaflet(map_data) %>% addTiles() %>% # Add default OpenStreetMap tiles setView(lng = 0, lat = 8, zoom = 5) %>% # Center on West Africa # Add circle markers for each city addCircleMarkers( ~long, ~lat, radius = ~sqrt(total_cases)/3, # Size based on sqrt of cases color = "black", weight = 1, fillColor = ~pal(total_cases), fillOpacity = 0.7, popup = ~paste( "", city, ", ", country, "
", "Total cases: ", total_cases, "
", "Human cases: ", human_cases, "
", "Rodent cases: ", rodent_cases, "
", "Avg. fitness: ", round(avg_fitness, 2) ) ) %>% # Add a legend addLegend( position = "bottomright", pal = pal, values = ~total_cases, title = "Total Cases", opacity = 0.7 ) # Save the map saveWidget(lassa_map, "lassa_geographic_map.html", selfcontained = TRUE) # Display the map lassa_map ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # Install required packages if (!require("networkD3")) install.packages("networkD3") ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Loading required package: networkD3 ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Attaching package: 'networkD3' ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` The following object is masked from 'package:htmlwidgets': JS ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` The following object is masked from 'package:leaflet': JS ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} if (!require("igraph")) install.packages("igraph") # Load libraries library(networkD3) library(igraph) library(dplyr) # Prepare data for the network visualization # We'll create a sample of transmissions for clarity set.seed(123) # For reproducibility # Get unique strains and clades strains <- unique(lassa_data$strain) transmission_sample <- lassa_data %>% filter(transmission %in% c("rodent-human", "human-human")) %>% sample_n(min(500, nrow(.))) # Take a sample to avoid overcrowding # Create edges (from-to connections) # For human-human transmissions, we'll simulate connections based on generation sequence edges <- data.frame(source = character(), target = character(), value = numeric(), type = character()) for (strain in strains) { strain_data <- transmission_sample %>% filter(strain == !!strain) if (nrow(strain_data) > 1) { # Sort by generation strain_data <- strain_data %>% arrange(generation) # Create connections between consecutive generations for (i in 1:(nrow(strain_data)-1)) { # Only connect if they could be related (later generation) if (strain_data$generation[i+1] > strain_data$generation[i]) { edges <- rbind(edges, data.frame( source = strain_data$clade[i], target = strain_data$clade[i+1], value = 1, type = strain_data$transmission[i+1] )) } } } } # Create nodes dataframe nodes <- transmission_sample %>% select(clade, strain, host, fitness) %>% distinct() %>% mutate(group = as.integer(factor(strain))) # Match node indices for the network edges$source_id <- match(edges$source, nodes$clade) - 1 edges$target_id <- match(edges$target, nodes$clade) - 1 # Filter out any NA relationships edges <- edges %>% filter(!is.na(source_id) & !is.na(target_id)) # Create the force network force_network <- forceNetwork( Links = edges, Nodes = nodes, Source = "source_id", Target = "target_id", NodeID = "clade", Group = "group", Value = "value", Nodesize = "fitness", opacity = 0.8, linkColour = ifelse(edges$type == "human-human", "#E69F00", "#56B4E9"), zoom = TRUE, legend = TRUE, bounded = TRUE, fontSize = 12, charge = -50 ) # Save the network visualization saveWidget(force_network, "lassa_transmission_network.html", selfcontained = TRUE) # Display the network force_network ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # Install required packages if (!require("plotly")) install.packages("plotly") # Load libraries library(plotly) library(dplyr) library(lubridate) # Convert date strings to Date objects lassa_data$date <- as.Date(lassa_data$date) # Create a sample for better visualization set.seed(42) spatial_sample <- lassa_data %>% arrange(date) %>% sample_n(min(3000, nrow(.))) # Create hover text spatial_sample$hover_text <- paste( "Date:", spatial_sample$date, "
", "Location:", spatial_sample$city, ",", spatial_sample$country, "
", "Host:", spatial_sample$host, "
", "Strain:", spatial_sample$strain, "
", "Transmission:", spatial_sample$transmission ) # Create the spatial plot spatial_plot <- plot_ly( data = spatial_sample, x = ~long, y = ~lat, z = ~as.numeric(date - min(date)) / 7, # Convert to weeks since first case type = "scatter3d", mode = "markers", marker = list( size = 5, color = ~as.numeric(date), # Color by date colorscale = "Viridis", opacity = 0.7 ), text = ~hover_text, hoverinfo = "text", color = ~as.factor(host) ) %>% layout( title = "Spatial-Temporal Spread of Lassa Virus", scene = list( xaxis = list(title = "Longitude"), yaxis = list(title = "Latitude"), zaxis = list(title = "Weeks Since First Case") ), legend = list(title = list(text = "Host")) ) %>% colorbar(title = "Date") ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Warning in RColorBrewer::brewer.pal(N, "Set2"): minimal value for n is 3, returning requested palette with 3 different levels Warning in RColorBrewer::brewer.pal(N, "Set2"): minimal value for n is 3, returning requested palette with 3 different levels ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Warning: Didn't find a colorbar to modify. ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} # Save the plot htmlwidgets::saveWidget( as_widget(spatial_plot), "lassa_spatial_temporal_spread.html", selfcontained = TRUE ) # Display the plot spatial_plot ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # Install required packages if (!require("plotly")) install.packages("plotly") if (!require("tidyr")) install.packages("tidyr") # Load libraries library(plotly) library(dplyr) library(lubridate) library(tidyr) # Prepare data for strain evolution plot evolution_data <- lassa_data %>% group_by(strain, date = as.Date(date)) %>% summarize( cases = n(), avg_fitness = mean(fitness), human_cases = sum(host == "human"), rodent_cases = sum(host == "rodent"), .groups = 'drop' ) %>% arrange(date) # Create the strain evolution plot evolution_plot <- plot_ly() %>% layout( title = "Evolution of Lassa Virus Strains Over Time", xaxis = list(title = "Date"), yaxis = list(title = "Number of Cases"), hovermode = "closest", legend = list(title = list(text = "Virus Strain")) ) # Add each strain as a trace for (strain in unique(evolution_data$strain)) { strain_data <- evolution_data %>% filter(strain == !!strain) evolution_plot <- evolution_plot %>% add_trace( data = strain_data, x = ~date, y = ~cases, type = "scatter", mode = "lines+markers", name = strain, line = list(shape = "spline", smoothing = 0.3), marker = list( size = ~sqrt(avg_fitness) * 5, opacity = 0.7 ), hoverinfo = "text", text = ~paste( "Strain:", strain, "
", "Date:", date, "
", "Total Cases:", cases, "
", "Human Cases:", human_cases, "
", "Rodent Cases:", rodent_cases, "
", "Avg Fitness:", round(avg_fitness, 2) ) ) } # Add fitness as a secondary y-axis evolution_plot_fitness <- evolution_data %>% group_by(date, strain) %>% summarize( avg_fitness = mean(avg_fitness), .groups = 'drop' ) %>% pivot_wider( names_from = strain, values_from = avg_fitness, values_fill = list(avg_fitness = NA) ) %>% plot_ly() %>% layout( title = "Fitness Evolution of Lassa Virus Strains", xaxis = list(title = "Date"), yaxis = list(title = "Fitness (R0)"), hovermode = "closest" ) for (strain in unique(evolution_data$strain)) { strain_data <- evolution_data %>% filter(strain == !!strain) %>% arrange(date) if (nrow(strain_data) > 0) { evolution_plot_fitness <- evolution_plot_fitness %>% add_trace( x = strain_data$date, y = strain_data$avg_fitness, type = "scatter", mode = "lines", name = strain, line = list(shape = "spline", smoothing = 0.3) ) } } # Create a subplot combining cases and fitness combined_evolution_plot <- subplot( evolution_plot, evolution_plot_fitness, nrows = 2, heights = c(0.6, 0.4), shareX = TRUE ) # Save the evolution plot htmlwidgets::saveWidget( as_widget(combined_evolution_plot), "lassa_strain_evolution.html", selfcontained = TRUE ) # Display the combined plot combined_evolution_plot ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # Install required packages if (!require("plotly")) install.packages("plotly") if (!require("lubridate")) install.packages("lubridate") # Load libraries library(plotly) library(dplyr) library(lubridate) # Prepare data for calendar heatmap lassa_data$date <- as.Date(lassa_data$date) # Aggregate by day and host type calendar_data <- lassa_data %>% group_by(date, host) %>% summarize( cases = n(), .groups = 'drop' ) %>% tidyr::complete( date = seq.Date(min(lassa_data$date), max(lassa_data$date), by = "day"), host = c("human", "rodent"), fill = list(cases = 0) ) %>% mutate( year = year(date), month = month(date), day = day(date), weekday = wday(date), week = week(date) ) # Create a heatmap for human cases human_heatmap <- calendar_data %>% filter(host == "human") %>% plot_ly( x = ~weekday, y = ~week, z = ~cases, type = "heatmap", colorscale = "YlOrRd", hoverinfo = "text", text = ~paste( "Date:", date, "
", "Human Cases:", cases ) ) %>% layout( title = "Human Lassa Virus Cases by Day", xaxis = list( title = "", tickvals = 1:7, ticktext = c("Sun", "Mon", "Tue", "Wed", "Thu", "Fri", "Sat") ), yaxis = list( title = "Week Number", autorange = "reversed" # To have week 1 at the top ) ) # Create a heatmap for rodent cases rodent_heatmap <- calendar_data %>% filter(host == "rodent") %>% plot_ly( x = ~weekday, y = ~week, z = ~cases, type = "heatmap", colorscale = "Blues", hoverinfo = "text", text = ~paste( "Date:", date, "
", "Rodent Cases:", cases ) ) %>% layout( title = "Rodent Lassa Virus Cases by Day", xaxis = list( title = "", tickvals = 1:7, ticktext = c("Sun", "Mon", "Tue", "Wed", "Thu", "Fri", "Sat") ), yaxis = list( title = "Week Number", autorange = "reversed" # To have week 1 at the top ) ) # Combine into a subplot calendar_plot <- subplot( human_heatmap, rodent_heatmap, nrows = 2, heights = c(0.5, 0.5), shareX = TRUE ) %>% layout( title = "Calendar Heatmap of Lassa Virus Cases" ) # Save the calendar heatmap htmlwidgets::saveWidget( as_widget(calendar_plot), "lassa_calendar_heatmap.html", selfcontained = TRUE ) # Display the heatmap calendar_plot ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # Install required packages if (!require("igraph")) install.packages("igraph") if (!require("ggraph")) install.packages("ggraph") ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Loading required package: ggraph ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} if (!require("tidygraph")) install.packages("tidygraph") ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Loading required package: tidygraph ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Attaching package: 'tidygraph' ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` The following object is masked from 'package:igraph': groups ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` The following object is masked from 'package:stats': filter ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} if (!require("viridis")) install.packages("viridis") ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Loading required package: viridis ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Loading required package: viridisLite ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} if (!require("htmlwidgets")) install.packages("htmlwidgets") if (!require("plotly")) install.packages("plotly") # Load libraries library(igraph) library(ggraph) library(tidygraph) library(dplyr) library(viridis) library(htmlwidgets) library(plotly) # Read the data lassa_data <- read.csv("lassa_virus_simulation_data.csv") # Prepare data for the network visualization set.seed(42) # For reproducibility # Create a subset of clades for clearer visualization # Sample based on strain to ensure all strains are represented strains <- unique(lassa_data$strain) clade_sample <- data.frame() for (strain in strains) { # Get data for this strain strain_data <- lassa_data %>% filter(strain == !!strain) %>% distinct(clade, .keep_all = TRUE) # Sample clades from this strain (adjust sample size for visual clarity) sample_size <- min(150, nrow(strain_data)) strain_sample <- strain_data %>% sample_n(sample_size) # Add to our overall sample clade_sample <- rbind(clade_sample, strain_sample) } # Create nodes dataframe nodes <- clade_sample %>% select(clade, strain, host, fitness) %>% distinct() # Create edges based on genetic similarity and transmission patterns edges <- data.frame(from = character(), to = character(), weight = numeric()) # For each strain, create connections between clades for (strain in unique(nodes$strain)) { strain_nodes <- nodes %>% filter(strain == !!strain) if (nrow(strain_nodes) > 1) { # Create a sample of connections within the strain n_connections <- min(nrow(strain_nodes) * 2, 200) # Limit connections for visual clarity for (i in 1:n_connections) { # Select two random nodes from the strain selected_nodes <- strain_nodes %>% sample_n(2) # Add edge with weight based on similarity (inverse of fitness difference) fitness_diff <- abs(selected_nodes$fitness[1] - selected_nodes$fitness[2]) weight <- 1 / (fitness_diff + 0.1) # Add small constant to avoid division by zero edges <- rbind(edges, data.frame( from = selected_nodes$clade[1], to = selected_nodes$clade[2], weight = weight )) } } } # Create a few connections between strains to show potential recombination/mutation events for (i in 1:10) { # Select two random nodes from different strains strain1 <- sample(strains, 1) strain2 <- sample(strains[strains != strain1], 1) node1 <- nodes %>% filter(strain == strain1) %>% sample_n(1) node2 <- nodes %>% filter(strain == strain2) %>% sample_n(1) # Add edge with lower weight (represents less common transition) edges <- rbind(edges, data.frame( from = node1$clade, to = node2$clade, weight = 0.2 # Lower weight for inter-strain connections )) } # Create graph object graph <- graph_from_data_frame(d = edges, vertices = nodes, directed = FALSE) # Add node attributes V(graph)$color <- as.factor(V(graph)$strain) V(graph)$size <- V(graph)$fitness * 2 # Use the Fruchterman-Reingold layout for better clustering layout <- layout_with_fr(graph, niter = 1000) # Create a static plot first to see the structure static_plot <- ggraph(graph, layout = "fr") + geom_edge_link(aes(alpha = weight), color = "lightgray", width = 0.5) + geom_node_point(aes(color = strain, size = fitness)) + scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1") + theme_graph() + labs(title = "Lassa Virus Transmission Network") + theme(legend.position = "right") # Save the layout coordinates for use in the interactive plot coords <- layout_with_fr(graph, niter = 1000) # Create node information for interactive plot node_info <- as_data_frame(graph, what = "vertices") node_info$x <- coords[,1] node_info$y <- coords[,2] node_info$id <- 1:nrow(node_info) # Create edge information edge_info <- as_data_frame(graph, what = "edges") edge_info$id <- 1:nrow(edge_info) # Add source and target IDs based on node IDs from_indices <- match(edge_info$from, node_info$clade) to_indices <- match(edge_info$to, node_info$clade) # Create a color mapping for the strains strain_colors <- c("#E41A1C", "#FF7F00", "#377EB8", "#4DAF4A", "#984EA3", "#FFFF33") names(strain_colors) <- sort(unique(node_info$strain)) # Create the interactive plot with plotly network_plot <- plot_ly() %>% # Add edges add_trace( type = "scatter", mode = "lines", x = c(rbind(node_info$x[from_indices], node_info$x[to_indices], rep(NA, length(from_indices)))), y = c(rbind(node_info$y[from_indices], node_info$y[to_indices], rep(NA, length(from_indices)))), line = list(color = "rgba(190, 190, 190, 0.3)", width = 0.5), hoverinfo = "none", showlegend = FALSE ) %>% # Add nodes add_trace( type = "scatter", mode = "markers", x = node_info$x, y = node_info$y, marker = list( size = 8 + node_info$fitness * 2, color = unname(strain_colors[node_info$strain]), line = list(color = "#FFFFFF", width = 0.5) ), text = paste( "Clade:", node_info$clade, "
", "Strain:", node_info$strain, "
", "Host:", node_info$host, "
", "Fitness:", round(node_info$fitness, 2) ), hoverinfo = "text", showlegend = FALSE ) # Add traces for the legend for (strain in unique(node_info$strain)) { network_plot <- network_plot %>% add_trace( type = "scatter", mode = "markers", x = c(NA), y = c(NA), marker = list(size = 10, color = strain_colors[strain]), name = strain, showlegend = TRUE ) } # Update layout network_plot <- network_plot %>% layout( title = "Lassa Virus Transmission Network", xaxis = list(title = "", showgrid = FALSE, zeroline = FALSE, showticklabels = FALSE), yaxis = list(title = "", showgrid = FALSE, zeroline = FALSE, showticklabels = FALSE), hovermode = "closest", legend = list(title = list(text = "Strains")), margin = list(l = 0, r = 0, b = 0, t = 50) ) # Save the plot htmlwidgets::saveWidget( as_widget(network_plot), "lassa_transmission_network.html", selfcontained = TRUE ) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Warning: Ignoring 1 observations Warning: Ignoring 1 observations Warning: Ignoring 1 observations Warning: Ignoring 1 observations Warning: Ignoring 1 observations ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} # Display the plot network_plot ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Warning: Ignoring 1 observations Warning: Ignoring 1 observations Warning: Ignoring 1 observations Warning: Ignoring 1 observations Warning: Ignoring 1 observations ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
